{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496656"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:53:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:53:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1402"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1402"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.8,0.02,0.14,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1402"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52595"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1402"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1402"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37957"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"197"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1569"},{"type":"tags","id":"2079"},{"type":"tags","id":"4957"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1419"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1742"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15328"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42307"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44705"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52595"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after being involved in a motor vehicle accident. Her legs were trapped under the car for several hours before being freed. She complains of a racing heart. She has a medical history of hypertension. Her only regular medication is perindopril.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 98/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 35.5\u00b0C. Her airway is patent. There is equal bilateral air entry on chest auscultation. Her central capillary refill time is 3 seconds. She is alert with equal and reactive pupils. Her blood glucose is 6.2 mmol/L. There is extensive bruising and lacerations to both lower limbs. On catheter insertion, her urine is very dark. An ECG shows tall tented T waves, loss of P waves, and widening of the QRS complex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVenous blood gas analysis reveals:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH: 7.30 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpO2: 42 mmHg (30-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpCO2: 25 mmHg (40-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO3-: 12 mmol/L (22-28)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENa+: 136 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EK+: 8.0 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECl-: 105 mmol/L (100-109)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Calcium gluconate 10% 10 mL intravenously","Oral calcium resonium 30 g","Normal saline 1 L intravenously","Insulin infusion 1 unit/kg","Amiodarone 300 mg intravenously"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms consistent with rhabdomyolysis and severe hyperkalaemia following a crush injury. The dark urine, ECG changes, and elevated serum potassium are key indicators. In this scenario, the most critical initial step is to stabilise the cardiac membrane to prevent potentially fatal arrhythmias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium gluconate 10% 10 mL intravenously\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial management. It rapidly stabilises the cardiac membrane, reducing the risk of arrhythmias associated with severe hyperkalaemia. This is crucial when serum potassium exceeds 6.5 mmol/L or when ECG changes of hyperkalaemia are present, as in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral calcium resonium\u003C/strong\u003E is used to remove potassium from the body via the gastrointestinal tract. However, it takes several hours to work and is not suitable as an initial treatment for severe, life-threatening hyperkalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal saline 1 L intravenously\u003C/strong\u003E would help address the patient\u0027s hypovolaemia and could assist in renal excretion of potassium. However, membrane stabilisation takes priority over volume resuscitation in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulin infusion\u003C/strong\u003E promotes the intracellular shift of potassium, lowering serum levels. While this is an important part of hyperkalaemia management, it is not the first step and should follow calcium administration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmiodarone\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered if this were a ventricular arrhythmia, given the wide QRS complex. However, the ECG changes are more consistent with hyperkalaemia, and calcium gluconate is the priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter administering calcium gluconate, further management would include insulin with dextrose to shift potassium intracellularly, sodium bicarbonate if acidotic, and potentially emergent dialysis. Aggressive fluid resuscitation is also crucial in managing rhabdomyolysis to prevent acute kidney injury. The underlying crush injury will require surgical evaluation and management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cardiac membrane stabilisation with calcium gluconate is essential when the serum potassium exceeds 6.5 mmol/L or when ECG changes of hyperkalaemia are present.","Rhabdomyolysis is a serious complication of crush injuries, leading to the release of intracellular components including potassium.","ECG changes of hyperkalaemia include tall tented T waves, loss of P waves, and widening of the QRS complex."],"references":["Nickson C. Hyperkalaemia management. In: Life in the Fast Lane [online]. 2020 Nov 3 [cited 2021 Feb 18]. Available at: https://litfl.com/hyperkalaemia-management/","Rajagopalan S. Crush Injuries and the Crush Syndrome. Med J Armed Forces India. 2010 Oct;66(4):317-20. doi: 10.1016/S0377-1237(10)80007-3. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4919827/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37957"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1402"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37957","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37957"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-07T12:08:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-08T20:33:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1402"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52595"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","l